We want to thank you for your continued patience. In conjunction with the district office we have expended every effort to correct the scheduling conflict for the May 18 Prom.

We have been able to confirm that our Prom WILL be held on Saturday, May 18 at the California Science Center in Los Angeles. The Prom is scheduled to begin at 7:00 pm and end at 11:00 pm.

Please note this is at the same address - California Science Center 700 Exposition Park Drive, Los Angeles as indicated on the dance contract.

We would like to thank the students, parents, and the district office as we partner together to make this a memorable and enjoyable evening. Please again, accept our sincere apology for the confusion and inconvenience.

post_text:
It has come to the Districtâ€™s attention that some Temple City residents are being approached by persons claiming to be ROP (LA County Regional Occupational Program) students. These interactions have included solicitations to purchase gift cards that will be mailed at a later date and requesting a $10 donation. Please be advised that this is NOT a valid fundraising effort. TCUSD no longer has ROP.

Unfortunately, this is not the first time our community has been targeted. Please note that District administration advises all of its teams and clubs to refrain from making door to door solicitations. If there is ever a doubt, always ask to see a current student ID. Our school offices are here to help if you have questions regarding the legitimacy of groups asking for donations on behalf of school programs.

We kindly ask that you share this information with your fellow community members.

post_text: A #MustSee for all those busy preparing for the start of school tomorrow. This story is a true lesson in the strength of positivity. #WeAreTCUSD
shared_text:
Association of California School Administrators
August 28, 2018 at 9:30 AM Â·

Federico Hernandez does not want your sympathy. He does not want your pity. He simply wants to be treated like everyone else. Federico has been blind as long as he can remember. He was diagnosed with retinoblastoma, a rare form of eye cancer that nearly cost him his life.

â€œYou learn to live with darkness that you live with every day,â€ Federico said. â€œYou just have to live your life as normal as you can.â€

No one can question the grit of Federico Hernandez. A two-time cancer survivor, Federico is determined to not be seen as someone with a disability, but as someone who is an equal.

â€œHeâ€™s been through quite a bit as a person. Heâ€™s gone through a lot of physical hardships and emotional hardships. And it inspires me because he bounces right back up literally and figuratively. And I hope to be like him when I grow up.â€ - Longden Elementary co-principal and former Temple City High School assistant principal
Aaron Chang ACSA Region XV

Longden Avenue PTA is with Mary Sneed.
June 6, 2018 at 10:07 PM Â·

Thank you to Mrs.Tom, Mrs. Schmidt, and Mrs. Sneed for all their time, talents, and contributions to our children.
Mrs. Tom has been at Longden for over 20 years and has been an involved and engaged PTA member as both a parent and a teacher.
Mrs. Schmidt (and Chiquita) has greeted students with a smile nearly every morning and been there to guide and focus the kids.
Mrs. Sneed has demonstrated and modeled the importance of community involvement and helped excite the kids on how they can contribute to their community in positive ways.
Thank you to all of these wonderful women and Longden PTA wishes you a very happy retirement!

post_text:
NOTICE: Beware â€˜ROPâ€™ Fundraising Scam

It has come to our attention that some Temple City residents are being approached by persons claiming to be ROP (LA County Regional Occupational Program) students. These interactions have included solicitations to purchase gift cards that will be mailed at a later date and requesting a $10 donation. Please be advised that this is NOT a valid fundraising effort. TCUSD no longer has ROP.

Unfortunately, scams like this are becoming more and more common. It is for this reason that District administration advises all of its teams and clubs to refrain from making door to door solicitations. If there is ever a doubt, always ask to see a current student ID. Our school offices are here to help if you have questions regarding the legitimacy of groups asking for donations on behalf of school programs.

A special ACSA Region XV Awards Dinner was held Monday evening. It was big night for Temple City as we saw two of our best honored at the event. Congratulations to Federico Hernandez and his family. The Temple City High School sophomore was honored with the Every Student Succeeding Award.

Friend of the District, Jerry Jambazian was also on hand at the event to receive the award in Outstanding Media Coverage. Join us in celebrating two honors well deserved.

Over the last 24 hours, districts across the United States have received email threats. Temple City Unified received one approximately an hour ago. The threat has been vetted by the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department and determined not to be credible.

The email originated in the United Kingdom and was duplicated and distributed throughout the United States.
